John Edward: Knowledge of languages is crucial for global citizens
Scottish independent schools enjoy the fame of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding results on exams further bolstered by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, the chosen career path and the city they have as a global citizen.
As a sector of education that can shape and implement a customized school program, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the conversation will impress his memory.
But if you talk to a man in his mother tongue, the words are imprinted in his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely only on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results of recent exams show that languages are at the top of the charts with the highest levels of achievement in independent schools.
68 percent of the students who learned a foreign language achieved an excellent score.
The data collected in 74 schools of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72 percent of students achieved an excellent grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of students received an excellent grade in German, 69 percent received an excellent grade in French, and 63 percent in French.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as optional subjects in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of physics, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Training Commission in 2014 showed that, for the reasons why employers are struggling to fill their vacancies, 17 per cent of the job losses are attributable to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the knowledge of languages is becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future career path.
In the future employment opportunities that require language skills, these skills are essential in the global world.
If one learns another language, no matter the career path he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries has an automatic advantage over competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK showed that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak, with French being the only language spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
With knowledge of several languages, especially those from developing countries, children have a better chance of finding a suitable job.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest in independent schools, it will always be possible to choose from a number of languages taught by experts in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the knowledge they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
In the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must also be expressed in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as ‘international communication skills’.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
