HIV/AIDS: China reports 14 per cent increase in new cases
China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
Health officials say more than 820,000 people have been affected in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
In the vast majority of new cases, the disease has been transmitted through sexual intercourse, which is a change compared to the past.
In some parts of China, the HIV virus has spread rapidly due to transfusions of infected blood.
However, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Junan Province, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has decreased to almost nothing.
The number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China is still increasing by 100,000 a year.
The transmission of HIV with sexual intercourse is a very common problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against people from the LGBT community is still very much present.
Because conservative values still apply in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men, according to the results of the research, eventually marry a woman.
The disease is often transmitted due to inadequate protection in sexual relations in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised general access to medicines for the treatment of HIV as part of its efforts to solve the problem.
