The latest project of this technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that builds on Berners’ solid open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who has access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupta’s purpose was to “take over the world.”
“We decided to do it now,” he said of the new company.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid platform technology, which allows users to create a “personal storage storage” or POD.
This may include contact information, task lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available in one browser and at the same time.
The peculiarity of the personal data storage is that the user can fully determine who can access what information.
This is what the company calls “personal data empowerment”.
Executive Director John Bruce says that the idea of the company is to bring together resources, processes and relevant skills that will enable access to the Solid platform for everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few hired developers to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Already this week, technology developers around the world could create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and the group “are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether they could introduce a complete change that could eliminate all their business models overnight.”
“We don’t ask for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a Saturday post on Medium that Inrupt’s purpose is “to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet with the establishment of the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
In recent months Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on Internet neutrality.
Berners-Lee will also remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the World Wide Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about the next era of the internet,” Berners-Lee added.
